\begin_layout Section*
R2 - Review of “ICTs to Provide Agricultural Advice to Smallholder Farmers:
 Experimental Evidence from Uganda” 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summary: The paper investigates the potential of Information and Communication
 Technologies (ICTs) for agricultural extension.
 In particular, the authors test whether alternative ICTs can enhance farmers’
 knowledge of improved practices, increase the adoption of such practices,
 and improve yields.
 They set up a field experiment where a random group of farmers was assigned
 to a treatment group which received access to a video (screened on a tablet
 by an enumerator) with agricultural advice.
 Farmers in the treatment group were further split into two groups: one
 was part of an encouragement design to use an interactive voice response
 (IVR) technology and the other one was not.
 The encouragement design promoted farmers’ access to on-demand pre-recorded
 messages on their phones with the same agricultural advices as the video
 intervention.
 Additionally, a randomly selected subgroup of those in the encouragement
 group were assigned to receive eight text messages around the time of some
 important agricultural practices related to the overall extension campaign.
 This design allows the authors to test: (a) the impact of the video extension
 program, (b) the incremental effect of the IVR system, and (c) the additional
 impact of the text message reminders.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, they find that the video intervention increased farmers’ knowledge
 of practices, improved the likelihood of adopting recommended practices,
 and raised yields.
 However, they find that the IVR and text message components generated little
 further improvements in these outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
General Comment: I enjoyed reading the paper and believe it makes a useful
 contribution to the emerging literature on the role of ICTs in agricultural
 extension.
 In my view, its biggest contribution is testing the joint effectiveness
 of different types of ICTs (when most the available work focuses only on
 one).
 Methodologically, the authors are able to estimate causal estimates based
 on randomized assign- ment.
 They are also rigorous in their inference by using increasingly popular
 techniques (based on randomization inference and adjusting for family-wise
 error rates).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suggestions: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 The paper is based on a traditional theory of change for agricultural extension
: extension leads to improvements of knowledge, which increases adoption
 of improved practices and subsequently boosts yields.
 Along this line, the paper would benefit from better translating this theory
 of change into their outcomes.
 For example, the paper’s outcomes for knowledge are plant spacing, input
 combination, timing of weeding, and fall armyworm control.
 While they do include some of these concepts in their adoption outcomes
 (i.e., spacing and weeding), there are several others — timing of planting,
 management of striga (though somewhat related 1to weeding), fertilizer
 use, and seed choices — for which there no measures of knowledge gains.
 Including outcomes related to the same practices in their analysis of adoption
 and knowledge would lend more credibility to the mechanisms through which
 ICT-based extension improves farming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 The paper would benefit from clarification of the research design.
 In particular, it would be useful to better understand why — in contrast
 to most recent field experiments on agricultural extension — the randomization
 was conducted at the individual rather than the village level.
 Information can flow easily between subjects and create externalities.
 While cluster randomization does not eliminate contamination of the control
 group, it reduces (inasmuch as possible) this flow of information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors find considerable impacts of their video intervention (especially
 for plant spacing), but no additional effects of the other ICTs (such as
 IVR).
 The IVR encouragement design was conducted through randomly providing some
 farmers with flyers incentivizing them to call a toll-free number and get
 agricultural information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can always argue that — if there are flows of information from the video
 to the control group — this would provide an underestimate of the treatment
 effect (given that it is already sizable and positive).
 But, the randomization strategy by itself may have a role to play in the
 IVR effect.
 Those with access to the extension videos may have shared the toll-free
 number with others.
 Because the video and IVR information have complementary effects (as implicitly
 assumed in the setup of the field experiment), those with information about
 the toll free number are more likely to have shared it with others that
 also had been in a video screening session.
 This would generate a downward bias of the treatment effect (which might
 be truly positive) of the IVR (consistent with the findings of the paper).
 Furthermore, text- message intervention was nested within the IVR encouragement
 design, this contamination can also downward bias the estimates of the
 text message campaign.
 
\end_layout

